01:26:05.376 --> 01:26:07.776
more than tax revenue
was at stake.

01:26:07.778 --> 01:26:09.611
The city wants
to improve the economy

01:26:09.613 --> 01:26:11.846
through tax revenue and jobs.

01:26:11.848 --> 01:26:13.849
But that cannot be
a justification

01:26:13.851 --> 01:26:15.617
for the use
of eminent domain.

01:26:15.619 --> 01:26:17.885
Then what
standard do you propose

01:26:17.887 --> 01:26:20.354
should draw a line
between when a city

01:26:20.356 --> 01:26:22.291
can take private land
and when they cannot?

01:26:22.293 --> 01:26:24.492
Municipalities should
never be able to take land

01:26:24.494 --> 01:26:26.627
- for private uses.
- <i>But every taking</i>

01:26:26.629 --> 01:26:27.996
has some public benefit,

01:26:27.998 --> 01:26:30.064
even if it's for private use.

01:26:30.066 --> 01:26:32.434
<i>So, given the fact
of the world,</i>

01:26:32.436 --> 01:26:34.670
why shouldn't the law
say virtually

01:26:34.672 --> 01:26:36.505
every taking is all right,

01:26:36.507 --> 01:26:38.840
<i>as long as there
is some public benefit?</i>

01:26:38.842 --> 01:26:40.408
Because, Your Honor,
then every property,

01:26:40.410 --> 01:26:42.743
every business,
every home can be taken

01:26:42.745 --> 01:26:43.879
for any private use.

01:26:43.881 --> 01:26:46.014
Only if there is a public use.

01:26:46.016 --> 01:26:47.983
And there almost always is.

01:26:47.985 --> 01:26:50.518
- <i>Do you agree with that?</i>
- <i>Do you want us to sit here</i>

01:26:50.520 --> 01:26:51.620
and evaluate the prospects

01:26:51.622 --> 01:26:54.055
of each condemnation,
one by one?

01:26:54.057 --> 01:26:55.191
<i>No, Your Honor.</i>

01:26:55.193 --> 01:26:57.591
Your Honors, I would like
to save my remaining time

01:26:57.593 --> 01:26:59.094
for after Mr. Harrigan's
arguments.

01:26:59.096 --> 01:27:01.499
Very well.
Mr. Harrigan.

01:27:04.967 --> 01:27:06.734
Your Honors.

01:27:06.736 --> 01:27:08.703
There is no principled basis
for a Court

01:27:08.705 --> 01:27:10.371
to make a value judgment
about a plan

01:27:10.373 --> 01:27:12.073
to revive an economically
depressed city.

01:27:12.075 --> 01:27:15.977
And where do you draw the line,
Mr. Harrigan?

01:27:15.979 --> 01:27:17.347
I wouldn't draw one.

